  "text": "The Django admin filter rendering pipeline works as follows:\n\n1. **Filter Definition**: RelatedFieldListFilter is defined in django/contrib/admin/filters.py (line 222) and inherits from FieldListFilter. It overrides the has_output() method (lines 248-253) to determine whether the filter should be displayed by checking if there are choices available: `return len(self.lookup_choices) + extra > 1` where extra accounts for nullable fields.\n\n2. **Base Filter Class**: The base ListFilter class is defined in django/contrib/admin/filters.py (line 26) with an abstract has_output() method (lines 41-47) that all filter subclasses must implement. This method returns True if the filter has content to display.\n\n3. **Filter Collection**: The ChangeList class in django/contrib/admin/views/main.py (line 67) collects filters in the get_filters() method (lines 175-277). At line 221, it explicitly checks `if spec and spec.has_output()` to determine which filter specs should be included in the filter_specs list. Only filters with has_output() returning True are appended to filter_specs (line 222). The get_queryset() method (lines 527-588) then unpacks the filters from get_filters() and stores them in self.filter_specs (line 530).\n\n4. **Template Rendering**: The change_list.html template in django/contrib/admin/templates/admin/change_list.html (line 72) iterates over the filters with `{% for spec in cl.filter_specs %}{% admin_list_filter cl spec %}{% endfor %}`. Each filter spec is passed to the admin_list_filter template tag, defined in django/contrib/admin/templatetags/admin_list.py (lines 520-529), which renders the filter using its associated template (typically admin/filter.html).\n\nThe key visibility control mechanism is RelatedFieldListFilter.has_output() which returns False when there are insufficient choices (only one choice or fewer) to filter by, preventing empty related-field filters from appearing in the sidebar."
}

